<ul>
<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino">X-ray: b/l AP, unilateral, lateral, b/l sunrise view</span></span></span></span></span></span></li>
<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino">Obtain X-rays in standing position (or joint space narrowing may not be apparent) </span></span></span></span></span></li>
<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino">MSK U/S: allows for dynamic imaging and is ≈100% sensitive for effusion </span></span></span></span></span></span></li>
<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino">Also visualizes ligaments, muscles/tendons, joint space, and vasculature </span></span></span></span></span></li>
<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino">MRI:  indicated after failure of conservative management or when considering surgical repair </span></span></span></span></span></span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino">Treatment: </span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<ul>
<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino">RICE (rest, ice, compression, elevation) for acute injuries </span></span></span></span></span></li>
<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino">Bracing </span></span></span></span></span></li>
<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino">NSAIDs: see prior section for anti-inflammatory dosing </span></span></span></span></span></li>
<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino">Physical therapy for 4-6 weeks for ligamentous, muscular, or meniscal injury  </span></span></span></span></span></li>
<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino">Antibiotics may be appropriate for bursitis if infection is suspected </span></span></span></span></span></li>
<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino">Referral to orthopedics/sports medicine if no improvement after conservative therapy</span></span></span></span></span>
<ul>
<li><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span style="vertical-align:baseline"><span style="font-family:Calibri,sans-serif"><span style="font-size:12.0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino">Surgery reserved for young, athletic people with ligamentous injury </span></span></span></span></span></span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
